In addition, the normalization to gold eliminates
further corrections due to:
* the dead time,
* knowledge of absolute solid angle value, and
* errors due to imperfect charge collection.
three surface barrier detectors with a 2.5
msr solid angle each were positioned at 118., 150.,
and 165.degr. The energy resolution of the detectors
used was 12 keV for protons in the measured energy
range.
The following factors were taken into
consideration for estimating the uncertainty:
* the counting statistics of the peak;
* systematic error in determining the N(Au)/N(N)
ratio.
Uncertainties due to dead time, solid angle, and
improper  charge measurement are eliminated with the
normalization to backscattering protons from gold.
Errors of the detector angular settings were estimated
to be negligible.
6.0 MV Tandem Van de Graaff accelerator
The beam was extracted from a sputtering ion source
using a TiH2. The proton beam delimited by
horizontal and vertical slits to a spot of 2 x 2 mm2
impinged on the sample at normal incidence. The
energy calibration of the accelerator was done using
narrow resonance in 27Al(p,gamma)28Si at 991.88 keV
and neutron threshold reaction 7Li(p,n)7Be at 1880.6
keV. Final energy spread of the beam was calculated
to be 0.1 % of the incident beam energy.
a thin AlN film deposited by reactive sputtering on
a vitreous graphite substrate was used. On the top,
a 6 nm Au layer was evaporated for normalization
purposes, assuming that cross sections for
backscattering of protons from Au are Rutherford in
the entire energy range studied.
